05179nam a22008175i 9780823269310DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232693107 a10.1515/97808232693102doi  a(DE-B1597)555308  a(OCoLC)953922122  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB828.25b.A45 2016 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a1492231 aAllen, William S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAesthetics of Negativity :bBlanchot, Adorno, and Autonomy /cWilliam S. Allen. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (338 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Abstract and Concrete Modernity -- t1. Autonomous Literature -- t2. The Obscurities of Artistic Innovation -- t3. Dead Transcendence -- t4. An Image of Thought in Thomas l'Obscur -- t5. Indifferent Reading in Aminadab -- t6. The Language-Like Quality of the Artwork -- t7. The Possibility of Speculative Writing -- t8. Echo Location -- t9. The Negativity of Thinking through Language -- tAppendix: Thomas l'Obscur, Chapter 1 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMaurice Blanchot and Theodor W. Adorno are among the most difficult but also the most profound thinkers in twentieth-century aesthetics. While their methods and perspectives differ widely, they share a concern with the negativity of the artwork conceived in terms of either its experience and possibility or its critical expression. Such negativity is neither nihilistic nor pessimistic but concerns the status of the artwork and its autonomy in relation to its context or its experience. For both Blanchot and Adorno negativity is the key to understanding the status of the artwork in post-Kantian aesthetics and, although it indicates how art expresses critical possibilities, albeit negatively, it also shows that art bears an irreducible ambiguity such that its meaning can always negate itself. This ambiguity takes on an added material significance when considered in relation to language as the negativity of the work becomes aesthetic in the further sense of being both sensible and experimental, and in doing so the language of the literary work becomes a form of thinking that enables materiality to be thought in its ambiguity.In a series of rich and compelling readings, William S. Allen shows how an original and rigorous mode of thinking arises within Blanchot's early writings and how Adorno's aesthetics depends on a relation between language and materiality that has been widely overlooked. Furthermore, by reconsidering the problem of the autonomous work of art in terms of literature, a central issue in modernist aesthetics is given a greater critical and material relevance as a mode of thinking that is abstract and concrete, rigorous and ambiguous. While examples of this kind of writing can be found in the works of Blanchot and Beckett, the demands that such texts place on readers only confirm the challenges and the possibilities that literary autonomy poses to thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAesthetics. 0aAutonomy (Philosophy) 0aContinental philosophy. 0aCritical theory. 0aNegativity (Philosophy) 4aAdorno. 4aBlanchot. 4aNegativity. 4aaesthetics. 4aambiguity. 4aautonomy. 4aliterature. 4amateriality. 4amodernity. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016z978311071186840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823269310zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyt